Where your vote counts

Dan MacKinlay

26/06/2021

In Australia, the party that gets to form government is chosen by who wins the most seats in the house of representatives, which comes down to winning the competition in most of federal electorates. But the competitions are much closer in some seats than others; Not all votes have the same importance when it comes to choosing the party which gets to run the country for the next few years. In some electorates the margin is very narrow, and the victorious candidate is chosen by no more voters than you can fit in a pub. Or to turn it around: If you live in one of those areas, your vote is very important, and you have a representative who really needs your support to keep their job. Next time you feel like the government is ignoring you, maybe you should consider moving to one of these marginal seats and see if your representative isn’t much more interested in hearing what you have to say.
